"Cecchinato L., Corradi M., Fornasieri E., Zamboni L.","Carbon dioxide as refrigerant for tap water heat pumps: A comparison with the traditional solution",2005,"International Journal of Refrigeration","28","8",,"1250","1258",,,10.1016/j.ijrefrig.2005.05.019,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-28844504358&partnerID=40&md5=8d573e349a9d33eb6d88d2ba77c62eb6","Dipartimento di Fisica Tecnica, Università degli Studi di Padova, Via Venezia, 1, I-35131 Padova, Italy","Cecchinato, L., Dipartimento di Fisica Tecnica, Università degli Studi di Padova, Via Venezia, 1, I-35131 Padova, Italy; Corradi, M., Dipartimento di Fisica Tecnica, Università degli Studi di Padova, Via Venezia, 1, I-35131 Padova, Italy; Fornasieri, E., Dipartimento di Fisica Tecnica, Università degli Studi di Padova, Via Venezia, 1, I-35131 Padova, Italy; Zamboni, L., Dipartimento di Fisica Tecnica, Università degli Studi di Padova, Via Venezia, 1, I-35131 Padova, Italy","Increased concern about the environmental impact of the refrigeration technology is leading toward design solutions aimed at improving the energy efficiency of the related applications, using eco-friendly refrigerants, i.e. ozone-friendly and with the least possible global warming potential (GWP). In this respect, carbon dioxide (ASHRAE R744) is seen today as one of the most promising refrigerants and is raising great interest in industrial and scientific fields. In the present work, the plant options are investigated, which are related to the design of air/water heat pumps for tap water using CO2. A comparison is made, in terms of energy efficiency, between a system working with CO2 and a similar one working with HFC R134a; such a comparison is carried out by means of a simulation model of a refrigerating machine/heat pump, characterized by a detailed representation of the heat exchangers, based on their subdivision into elementary volumes. Results show that carbon dioxide is an interesting substitute for synthetic fluids, if the design of the system is focused to take advantage of its properties. © 2005 Elsevier Ltd and IIR. All rights reserved.","CO2; Comparison; Heat pump; Heating; Hot water; Modelling; Optimization; R-134a; Simulation; Transcritical cycle; Water-water","Computer simulation; Energy efficiency; Environmental impact; Global warming; Heat exchangers; Heat pump systems; Optimization; Refrigerating machinery; Refrigeration; CO2; Comparison; Hot water; R-134A; Transcritical cycle; Water-water; Carbon dioxide",,,,,,"Lorentzen, G., Revival of carbon dioxide as a refrigerant (1994) Int J Refrigeration, 17 (5), pp. 292-301; Cavallini, A., Nekså, P., Prospects for the return of CO2 as a refrigerant (2001) VI° Congreso Iberoamericano de Aire Acondicionado y Refrigeración, CIAR, Buenos Aires, Argentina; Nekså, P., CO2 heat pump systems (2002) Int J Refrigeration, 25 (4), pp. 421-427; Groll, E.A., Review of recent research on the use of CO2 for air conditioning and refrigeration (2001) Clima 2000, Napoli, Italy; Fornasieri, E., Zilio, C., An aspect of the optimisation of condensers in refrigerating installations (in Italian) (1998) 39° Convegno Nazionale AICAAR, Milano, Italy; Fornasieri, E., Zilio, C., An advanced simulation model for optimising finned coils condensers (in Italian) (1998) Atti Del 53° Congresso Nazionale ATI, Firenze, Italy, 1; Rieberer, R., Kasper, G., Halozan, J., CO2 - A chance for once through heat pump heaters (1997) CO2 Technology in Refrigeration, Heat Pumps and Air Conditioning Systems, , IEA Heat Pump Centre Trondheim, Norway; Rieberer, R., Gassler, M., Halozan, H., Control of CO2 heat pumps (2000) 4th IIR-Gustav Lorentzen Conference on Natural Working Fluids, Purdue University, West Lafayette, in; Nekså, P., Rekstad, H., Zakeri, G.R., Schiefloe, P.A., CO2 - Heat pump water heater: Characteristics, system design and experimental results (1998) Int J Refrigeration, 21 (3), pp. 172-179; Heyl, P., Preusser, S., Kraus, W.E., The CO2 heat pump project at th